title: Denny Regrade, 1928
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Regrades. Denny Hill. 1928. Looking towards Denny School. 1928." The Denny School was located on Battery Street between 5th and 6th Avenues.

title: Columbia School, ca. 1910
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Schools. Columbia School. 723 South Concord Street. Built 1890; addition 1904; demolished 1959. Exterior. Frame. View of front from right side. Known also as the Pontius, later the Lowell School."

title: Employees of Kistler's Grocery, ca. 1890
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Portraits. Group. Employees of Kistler's Grocery. Ca. 1890-1900. Meyer Peyser, driver of grocery wagon; "Cad" White, store clerk; Anna Granger, bookkeeper; Fred Ihrig, butcher;Jimmy Moore, butcher boy." Transcribed from back of photograph: “KISTLERS GROCERY: Meyer Peyser, He drove the grocery wagon, Deceased. “Cad” White, the store clerk, Deceased.  Anna Granger, store bookkeeper-Living in Tacoma  Fred Ihrig, the butcher, living at Sand Point  Jimmy Moore, the butcher boy, living in Seattle”

title: Lonnie Austin, welterweight champion, ca. 1906
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Portraits. Austin, Lonnie, b. 1880. Welterweight champion of the Northwest, 1906." Transcribed from back of photograph: “LONNIE AUSTIN- was one of the best amateur boxers ever produced on the Pacific Coast. There are many who still insist he could have been a world champion had he turned professional."

title: View from 1st Ave. and Pike St. looking south 1878.
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Views. From 1st Ave. and Pike St., 1878. Looking south. Photo by Peiser, Theodore E.. Center background. Arlington Hotel; Yesler's mill & Yesler's dock; Wreck of bark "Windward" in front of dock; M.R. Moddock's bldg., left in front of trestle; R.H. Denny Home, n. side of Union St.; A.A. Denny Home, s. side of Union St.; Young naturalists first home, rear of A.A. Denny home."

title: Plymouth Church, ca. 1900
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Churches. Plymouth Church (Congregational) Northeast corner Third Ave. and University St. Built 1891-1892; demolished 1911. Exterior. Brick. Left side view. Territorial University in background. Photo by Webster & Stevens."

title: Yesler Way looking east, June 5, 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Streets. Yesler Ave. June 5, 1889. Looking east. Ziba C. Miles, Hardware, left foreground, Occidental Hotel in background. Photo taken the day before the fire."

title: Rainier School, ca. 1942
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Schools. Rainier School. 23rd S. & King. Built 1890; additions 1900, 1930; closed 1940; reopened as Building Trades Unit of Edison Technical School, 1943. Exterior. Frame. Three-quarter view of front and right side. Photo ca. 1942."
intersection: 23rd Ave. S. and S. King St.

title: View NW from Smith Tower, 1949
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Views. From Third Ave. and Cherry St. 1949. Panoramic view of Seattle business district, looking northeast. 1949." Transcribed from back of photograph: "1. Dexter Horton building.  2. Artic bldg.  3. Central bldg.  4. Northern Life bldg.  5. Telephone bldg.  6. Olympic Hotel.  7. Federal Court House.  8. Seattle General Hospital  9. First Methodist Church 10. Rainier Club  11. Y.M.C.A. 12. Seattle Public Library  13. Hungerford Hotel”
subjects: William Kenzo Nakamura United States Courthouse (Seattle, Wash.)

title: Seattle waterfront near Western Ave. and Columbia St., ca. 1880
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Waterfront. Ca. 1880. Looking west. Hulk of abandoned bark, Windward, in center. Photo by Webster & Stevens. Site approximately Western and Columbia." Transcribed from back of photograph: “Seattle's waterfront of the early 80's, showing the hulk of the abandoned Bark Windward, now buried beneath the foundations of the Colman Building.  The boys of the town used the old bark's hulk as their “first choice” swimming pavilion.”

title: First cable car, 1941
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Transportation. First cable car (# 13) Built 1888. Original Yesler car. Photo by Werner Lenggenhager, 1941. Seattle, Museum of History and Industry."
subjects: Museum of History and Industry (Seattle, Wash.)

title: View from James St. looking NW, ca. 1885
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Views. From James Street hill. Ca. 1885. Looking northwest. Territorial University in background."

title: Ross School, ca. 1940
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Schools. Ross School. North of Queen Anne Hill. Opened 1873; in use until ca. 1903; demolished 1941. Exterior. Wood. View of front from left side. Established on the second floor of the pioneer Ross home." The 1905 City Directory lists the Ross home at 619 W. 42nd St.

title: Yesler Way west from 3rd Ave., ca. 1892
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Streets. Yesler Ave. Ca. 1892. From Third Ave. looking west. Left foreground: Piper's bakery; right foreground: Crawford & Hannon, Real Estate."

title: Pacific School, ca. 1900
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Schools. Pacific School. 510-11th Ave. (1114 East Jefferson). Built 1893; additions in 1912, 1954. Exterior. Brick. View of front from right side. Ca. 1900."

title: Beacon Hill School, March 23, 1904
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Schools. Beacon Hill School. 2524- 16th Ave. South. Original school built 1899. Main building completed in 1904; addition 1912. Exterior. Frame. View of front from right side with main building still under construction. Photo taken March 23, 1904."

title: Fire at 1st Ave. and Madison St., June 6, 1889
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Fire. June 6, 1889. At place of origin. Front Street [1st Ave.] looking south from Madison St. Right foreground: Kenyon block, location of Seattle Times." Transcribed from back of photograph: “A new and rarely seen picture showing the start of the great Seattle fire on June 6, 1889.  Old Seattle Times was located in the Kenyon Block on right.  The Frye Hotel is hidden from view.  Drug store occupied corner where man is seen standing.”

title: View SE from Denny Hill, 1880
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Views. From Denny Hill. Ca. 1880. Looking southeast. Providence Hospital and Territorial University in background. Photo by Webster & Stevens."

description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Fire Department. First fire engine, a third-size Gould steamer, property of the pioneer volunteer fire department. 1879."

description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Parks. South Park. Duckpond. Ca. 1890-95."

description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Portraits. Group. Girls of Ray school. 1892."

title: Ray School, 1892
description: Transcribed from front of photograph: "Seattle Schools. Ray School. South of Van Asselt near Duwamish river. Exterior. Frame. Three quarter view of front from left side. 1892." Transcribed from back of photo: “The pioneer RAY SCHOOL was located just south of Van Asselt, where the old “valley” road crosses the Duwamish. Abandoned in recent years. In photo are Mrs. Ray, Clara, Dora, Ella, and Rhoda Ray, and Edith Clarke.  This picture was taken in 1892.”

title: Van Asselt School, ca. 1940
